 WASHING MACHINE n. Old-style hard disks in floor-standing cabinets. So
called because of the size of the cabinet and the "top-loading" access to the
media packs -- and, of coaurse, they were always set on "spin cycle". The
washing-machine idiom transcends language barriers; it's even used in Russian
hacker jargon. see WALKING DRIVES. The thick channel cables connecting these
were called BIT HOSE (see HOSE).